00:31:04.780 --> 00:31:07.780
AUDIENCE: Do you have any tips
for designing in a smaller

00:31:07.780 --> 00:31:09.270
space?

00:31:09.270 --> 00:31:10.280
PRESTON BAILEY: Yes.

00:31:10.280 --> 00:31:11.505
Yes, yes yes.

00:31:11.505 --> 00:31:14.160
There's such a
basic, simple trick

00:31:14.160 --> 00:31:17.110
about designing smaller space.

00:31:17.110 --> 00:31:19.980
Uplight the walls.

00:31:19.980 --> 00:31:21.260
You take this room.

00:31:21.260 --> 00:31:24.130
You notice that it's
in darkness right now.

00:31:24.130 --> 00:31:30.240
If I just uplit the walls,
immediately it gives it depth.

00:31:30.240 --> 00:31:32.870
And it's the same thing
with a small space.

00:31:32.870 --> 00:31:36.050
Immediately it starts
looking bigger.

00:31:36.050 --> 00:31:40.780
So visually it
changes immediately.

00:31:40.780 --> 00:31:44.130
Also, people make the
mistake that in small spaces,

00:31:44.130 --> 00:31:46.900
they put a lot of things in.

00:31:46.900 --> 00:31:48.090
You should do the opposite.

00:31:48.090 --> 00:31:50.450
Try to empty it as
much as possible

00:31:50.450 --> 00:31:53.520
and just create elements
that are valuable,

00:31:53.520 --> 00:31:58.500
elements that are going to
tell a story, a statement.

00:31:58.500 --> 00:32:00.210
But those are the
two basic things

00:32:00.210 --> 00:32:02.170
that I think are very
effective in creating

00:32:02.170 --> 00:32:04.360
a space that is not very big.

00:32:04.360 --> 00:32:08.885
And again, whenever you have any
question, just use candlelight.

00:32:12.140 --> 00:32:15.511
Uplight the walls, and
just use lots of candles.

